fields.description:
During the installation of Confluence using the Docker container we are using root permissions:
{code}def gen_cfg(tmpl, target, env, user='root', group='root', mode=0o644, overwrite=True):{code}

As a good practice, we should use non-root user in this case. As we already have confluence user and files are written by it, please change the entrypoint.py to use something like this:
{code}
def gen_cfg(tmpl, target, env, user='confluence', group='confluence', mode=0o644, overwrite=True)
{code}

h3. Problem Definition
Some of the Confluence operations use the spacekey within the URL as the example below:
 * Create page action: {{<Confluence Base URL>/pages/createpage.action?spaceKey=<SpaceKEY>&fromPageId=<pageID>&src=quick-create}}
 * Display page: {{<Confluence Base URL>/display/<SpaceKEY>/<PageTitle>}}

The information in the URL can be used to create some analytics information about Confluence usage, such busies Spaces and Pages.

The problem is that on some operations, the URL is not consistent and it doesn't display the {{Spacekey}}.
Below are some examples of these operations:
 * Edit page: {{<Confluence Base URL>/pages/editpage.action?pageId=<pageID>}}
 * View page information: {{<Confluence Base URL>/pages/viewinfo.action?pageId=<pageID>}}
 * View page action: {{<Confluence Base URL>/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=<pageID>}}

Refer to [Confluence URL list|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confkb/confluence-url-list-317949394.html] for other examples of this.

h3. Suggested Solution
Whenever an operation occurs within a Space, add the {{Spacekey}} in the URL, either as part of the path or as a query parameter.
 
h3. Workaround 
_None so far_

